    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/182d0ce855c8324a596648c04643e8f9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 267086,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 555045,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/555045/user555045",
                "reputation": 65818,
                "display_name": "user555045",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1436638022,
            "creation_date": 1436638022,
            "body": "<p>To summarize the comment chain, you could write<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>(a * k + b) % P &amp; (m - 1)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>which is <strong>not<\/strong> equivalent to the original expression, but meets the same requirements anyway. It handles the case that <code>a * k + b<\/code> is negative (either because <code>k<\/code> is negative or because of wrapping) differently, but in a way that is still fine for a hash function.<\/p>\n\n<p>In this new expression, the only remaining mod-operation is by a constant, which any respectable compiler optimizes along the same lines as it optimizes division by a constant.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 31360239,
            "question_id": 31358967
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d84b558fd67be10d5a718fb94231909d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 93689,
                "user_type": "moderator",
                "user_id": 256196,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/256196/bohemian",
                "reputation": 427464,
                "display_name": "Bohemian",
                "accept_rate": 77
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1436683932,
            "creation_date": 1436683932,
            "body": "<p>This gets a similar answer (\"similar\" means \"same result when bracketed expression is non-negative, but different when negative), but using bit kung fu to avoid the modulus division <em>and<\/em> the call to <code>Math.abs()<\/code>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>(a*k + b) % P &amp; ~-m\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>To see what's going on, let's assume <code>m = 8<\/code> and have a look at the 16-bit bit patterns:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>8   -&gt; 0000 1000\n-8  -&gt; 1111 1000\n~-8 -&gt; 0000 0111\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>As you can see, <code>~-m<\/code> produces the bit mask you need to mask off all but the bits needed for the result of <code>n % m<\/code> - ie the high bit (negative indicator bit) and all but the bits to the right of the 1 bit used for the power of 2 number.<\/p>\n\n<p>On a personal note, I am quite enamoured with the expression <code>~-m<\/code>, which when ANDed with the preceding calculation achieves both the <code>abs()<\/code> (by bit-masking off the high bit) and effectively does a modulus division when <code>m<\/code> is a power of two.<\/p>\n\n<p>The difference arises when the preceding result is negative, due to this approach treating negative as if they were positive.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 31365197,
            "question_id": 31358967
        }
    ],
